 SocialPredict has accounting-sensitive flows. That means the architecture must be explicit about transaction policy.

+### WAVE04 bet placement boundary
+
+As of Wednesday, April 29, 2026, bet placement is the first migrated accounting-sensitive workflow.
+
+The unit of work starts in `internal/repository/bets.GormRepository.PlaceBetTransaction` and commits only after the transaction callback returns nil. The transaction-scoped collaborators use the same `*gorm.DB` handle for:
+
+- reading the user balance
+- checking whether the user already has a bet in the market for initial-fee policy
+- debiting the user's account balance
+- inserting the bet row
+
+Those writes must commit together or roll back together. Bet placement no longer relies on a later refund as the primary correctness mechanism.
+
+The primary production DB concurrency protection is a Postgres `FOR UPDATE` lock on the user row before the balance check and debit. SQLite tests exercise rollback behavior without that dialect-specific lock.
+
+Generic automatic retry, circuit-breaker behavior, caching, and Redis remain out of scope for this wave.
+
+Remaining accounting-sensitive transaction inventory:
+
+- Sell position: still uses sale credit plus bet ledger insertion with compensation-style fallback and needs its own explicit unit of work around position read, sale valuation, account credit, and sale bet insertion.
+- Market resolution: still needs an explicit transaction surface around resolution state transition, winner accounting, and any payout writes so resolution cannot partially commit.
+- Startup seeds, migrations, and admin mutations remain separate database-layer concerns; they are not part of the bet-placement accounting boundary.
+
 ### What needs to improve

 The backend should define clear units of work for use cases such as:
